      Is the Dodge Challenger a Good Car?

      Yes, the Dodge Challenger is a good car. Its stable of engines is unmatched by nearly any other mainstream vehicle, and every offering is gold. An adult-friendly back seat and best-in-class trunk space give the Challenger a sefrelinse of utility that no other sports car provides, and the infotainment features are a breeze.

      It's not all good news, though. Many rival performance-oriented cars handle better than the Challenger, and this Dodge's interior can feel a bit uninspiring. Furthermore, the Challenger has a history of low safety scores, driven by subpar crash test results and a paltry list of driver assistance features.

      Should I Buy the Dodge Challenger?

      You should buy the Challenger if you want a fast, yet somewhat practical, modern muscle car. In terms of horsepower for your money, it's hard to beat this Dodge.

      We analyzed 73 Dodge Challenger reviews along with performance specs, fuel economy estimates, and more to help you decide if the 2022 Challenger is the right new car for you. This 2022 Challenger review incorporates applicable research for all models in this generation, which launched for 2008.

      2021 vs. 2022 Dodge Challenger: What's the Difference?

      There are no major differences between the 2022 and 2021 Dodge Challenger.

      Compare the 2021 and 2022 Challenger

      Here are the key changes for the Dodge Challenger over the last few years:

      • 2022: no notable changes
      • 2021: expanded availability of Widebody package
      • 2020: SRT Super Stock model introduced; 50th Anniversary Edition appearance packages became available; minor updates to interior and exterior styling
      • 2019: SRT Hellcat Redeye replaced SRT Demon model; R/T Scat Pack Widebody debuted; SRT Hellcat horsepower increased to 717 from 707
      • 2018: 7-inch touch screen, Android Auto, and Apple CarPlay became standard; SRT Hellcat Widebody and SRT Demon introduced

      If you're considering an older model, be sure to read our 2019 Challenger , 2020 Challenger , and 2021 Challenger reviews to help make your decision. Also, check out our Best New Car Deals and Best New Car Lease Deals pages to learn about savings and discounts you can find on new vehicles.

      How Much Does the Dodge Challenger Cost?

      As of this writing, Dodge has not announced pricing for the 2022 Challenger. Typically, the Challenger has one of the higher base prices among sports cars ; you can expect it to start at less than $30,000.

      Check out our U.S. News Best Price Program for great savings at your local Dodge dealer. You can also find excellent manufacturer incentives on our Dodge deals page .

      Dodge Challenger Versus the Competition

      Dodge Challenger vs. Chevrolet Camaro

      The main advantages that the Chevrolet Camaro has over the Challenger are in handling and price. The Chevy is more composed and agile than the lumbering Dodge, and it retails for several thousand dollars less. Both of these muscle cars have potent acceleration from their wide range of engines, as well as a similar list of features. They also have mediocre interior qualities. The Challenger offers a much roomier cabin and a larger trunk though, making it the better choice for everyday use.

      Compare the Challenger and Camaro

      Dodge Challenger vs. Ford Mustang

      The Ford Mustang is a top-ranked sports car thanks in part to its refined cabin and razor-sharp handling, two areas that it handily bests the Challenger in. The Mustang's top 760-horsepower model is one of the few that comes close to the Challenger SRT variants as well. You'll get more second-row space and a larger trunk with the Dodge, so if those are things you prioritize, buy the Challenger. For a more well-rounded muscle car, the Mustang is hard to beat.

      Compare the Challenger and Mustang

      Dodge Challenger vs. Dodge Charger

      The Dodge Charger competes in the large car class , and it's notable for offering many of the same hellacious engine options as the Challenger. The biggest difference is that the Charger is a four-door sedan, while the Challenger is a two-door muscle coupe. These two Dodges rate similarly for handling, interior quality, passenger space, and features, so your choice will likely come down to personal preference.

      Compare the Challenger and Charger

      Compare the Challenger, Camaro, and Mustang

      Challenger Performance: The Definition of Modern Muscle

      Challenger Engine

      With the Challenger, Dodge continues to be the final word in brutish engine options and pure power. The 2022 Challenger comes standard with a V6 engine, and its just over 300 horsepower is a good start to the lineup. It propels the car with authority but may not deliver all the oomph you want for such a bulky vehicle.

      A pair of naturally aspirated Hemi V8 engines at 375 and 485 horsepower are a better fit for the Challenger's character and provide strong, seamless acceleration. With horsepower ratings between 717 and 807, the Challenger Hellcat and Challenger SRT Super Stock models are drag-strip-worthy cars. These supercharged V8-powered models will throw you back in your seat when you hit the gas.

      Challenger Engine Options
      • Base engine: 3.6-liter V6 with 303 horsepower and 268 pound-feet of torque; (standard in SXT and GT)
      • Available engines:
        • 5.7-liter Hemi V8 with 375 horsepower and 410 pound-feet of torque; (standard in R/T)
        • 6.4-liter Hemi V8 with 485 horsepower and 475 pound-feet of torque; (standard in R/T Scat Pack)
        • 6.2-liter supercharged Hemi V8 with 717 horsepower and 656 pound-feet of torque; (standard in SRT Hellcat)
        • 6.2-liter high-output supercharged Hemi V8 with 797 horsepower and 707 pound-feet of torque; (standard in SRT Hellcat Redeye)
        • 6.2-liter high-output supercharged Hemi V8 with 807 horsepower and 707 pound-feet of torque; (standard in SRT Super Stock)
      • Drivetrain: standard rear-wheel drive; available all-wheel drive
      • Transmission: standard eight-speed automatic; available six-speed manual
      Challenger Performance Packages and Options:
      • Performance Handling package (available in GT and R/T): 20-inch Lights Out painted wheels, Brembo four-wheel ABS brakes with black calipers, a high-performance suspension, performance steering, a 3.09 or 3.90 axle, and an anti-spin differential
      • Dynamics package (available in R/T Scat Pack): six-piston Brembo front brakes and 20-inch painted aluminum wheels
      • SRT Performance Spoiler (available in R/T Scat Pack, SRT Hellcat, SRT Hellcat Redeye, and SRT Super Stock)
      • Rear Seat Delete package (available in SRT Hellcat, SRT Hellcat Redeye, and SRT Super Stock)
      • 1320 package (available in R/T Scat Pack): a drag mode, an adaptive suspension, and street-legal drag race tires and wheels
      Challenger Appearance Packages :
      • Blacktop package (available in SXT, GT, and R/T): 20-inch black painted alloy wheels, black grille and instrument cluster, a black rear spoiler, a black fuel door, trim-specific badging, and front fog lamps
      • Plus package (available in SXT, GT, R/T, R/T Scat Pack, SRT Hellcat, SRT Hellcat Redeye, and SRT Super Stock): 20-inch satin carbon painted wheels, bright pedals, ambient lights, and stitched instrument panel and doors
      • Shaker package (available in R/T and R/T Scat Pack): a Shaker under-hood decal, a gloss black grille, a Shaker hood and intake, and a satin black rear spoiler
      • T/A package (available in R/T and R/T Scat Pack): 20-inch low-gloss black wheels, a gloss black grille, a satin black rear spoiler, a functional hood scoop, unique body graphics, and a detailed instrument cluster
      • Performance Plus package (available in R/T): 20-inch forged/painted aluminum wheels and summer tires
      • Painted Black Satin Graphics package (available in SRT Hellcat, SRT Hellcat Redeye, and SRT Super Stock): satin black hood, roof, and deck lid
      • Laguna Leather package (available in SRT Hellcat, SRT Hellcat Redeye, and SRT Super Stock): Laguna leather seats with SRT Hellcat logo
      • Alcantara Appearance package (available in SRT Hellcat, SRT Hellcat Redeye, and SRT Super Stock): Alcantara/Laguna seats with SRT Hellcat logo and a Wild Wheel Alcantara steering wheel
      • Widebody package (available in R/T Scat Pack, SRT Hellcat, SRT Hellcat Redeye, and SRT Super Stock): widebody fender flares, a competition suspension, and 20-inch forged/painted wheels
      Challenger Gas Mileage

      Equipped with its standard V6 engine and rear-wheel drive, the 2022 Challenger gets an EPA-estimated 19 mpg in the city and 30 mpg on the highway. Those figures are about average for V6-powered rivals in the sports car class . Pairing the base engine with all-wheel drive drops fuel economy to 18 mpg in the city and 27 mpg on the highway.

      The 5.7-liter Challenger R/T gets up to 16/25 mpg city/highway, while the 6.4-liter R/T Scat Pack gets up to 15/24 mpg. The worst fuel economy in the lineup comes from the supercharged SRT models, at 13 mpg in the city and 21 or 22 mpg on the highway.

      Challenger Ride and Handling

      The Challenger is more at home going in a straight line than it is carving corners, as it exhibits a little more body roll and feels less agile than some nimbler muscle-car rivals. Its size can also make it trickier to maneuver in tight spots. Ride quality is better in lower-end models that have suspensions tuned more for comfort. As you move up in engine power, you'll find stiffer, performance-tuned chassis, which result in a harsher ride.

      How Fast Is the Challenger?

      The fastest Dodge Challenger is the SRT Super Stock, which can go from zero to 60 mph in 3.25 seconds and run a quarter-mile in 10.5 seconds. The Challenger SRT Super Stock is limited by its tires to a top speed of 168 mph.

      The Hellcat Redeye goes from zero to 60 in 3.4 seconds, and it has a top speed of 203 mph; the standard Hellcat has a top speed of 199 mph.

      Does the Challenger Have All-Wheel Drive?

      The Challenger comes standard with rear-wheel drive, and all-wheel drive is optional in models with the base V6 engine. Neither of this Dodge's primary rivals offer AWD at all.

      Read more about performance

      Challenger Interior: Coupes Don't Have to Be Cramped

      Challenger Interior Quality

      The 2022 Dodge Challenger's interior is pretty basic. There are some hard plastic surfaces especially in lower trims and the design lacks the freshness that you'd find in more recently updated rivals. Still, you can deck out the cabin with nicer touches, like Nappa leather upholstery and various suede trimmings.

      Challenger Infotainment, Bluetooth, and Navigation

      All Challengers come with the Uconnect infotainment system, which is regularly lauded for its ease of use. You might find the standard 7-inch touch screen and its graphics a little underwhelming; the optional 8.4-inch display is sharper, but many other brands have more brilliant and sleeker infotainment optics.

      • Standard infotainment features: a 7-inch touch screen, Bluetooth, Android Auto, Apple CarPlay, two USB ports, and a six-speaker stereo
      • Available infotainment features: an 8.4-inch touch screen, navigation, satellite radio, a six- or nine-speaker Alpine premium stereo, and an 18-speaker Harman Kardon surround-sound stereo
      • Additional standard features: dual-zone automatic climate control and proximity keyless entry
      • Other available features: a sunroof, remote start, and a universal garage door opener

      For more information, read What Is Apple CarPlay? and What Is Android Auto?

      Challenger Cargo Space

      The Challenger's 16.2-cubic-foot trunk is the largest in the sports car class , by far. It's enough for a few suitcases or plenty of shopping bags. While the opening is big and wide, the trunk lip is high, so you'll have to put in a little more effort when putting in heavy items.

      How Many People Does the Challenger Seat?

      The Dodge Challenger seats five people. The front seats are well-positioned for long cruising, but thick rear pillars can impede rearward visibility. The Challenger sticks out in the class for its incredibly roomy second row and ability to fit adults in comfort. This is one of the most spacious two-door cars on the market.

      Challenger and Child Car Seats

      There are three complete sets of LATCH connectors for the Challengers rear seats.

      Read more about interior

      Challenger Reliability

      Is the Dodge Challenger Reliable ?

      The 2022 Dodge Challenger has a predicted reliability score of 88out of 100. A J.D. Power predicted reliability score of 91-100 is considered the Best, 81-90 is Great, 70-80 is Average, and 0-69 is Fair and considered below average.

      Dodge Challenger Warranty

      Dodge covers the Challenger with a three-year/36,000-mile basic warranty and a five-year/60,000-mile powertrain warranty.

      Read more about reliability

      2022 Dodge Challenger Safety

      Score: 7.9/10
      Crash Test Results

      The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration gave the 2022 Dodge Challenger an overall safety rating of five out of five stars, with five stars in the side crash test and four stars in the frontal crash and rollover tests.

      The Insurance Institute for Highway Safety has not evaluated the 2022 Challenger, but it did crash test the nearly identical 2021 Challenger . That vehicle earned the highest rating of Good in two tests, the second-highest rating of Acceptable in the roof strength and head restraints and seats tests, and the second-lowest rating of Marginal in the drivers-side small overlap front test.

      Safety Features

      Standard driver assistance features:

      • Rearview camera

      Available driver assistance features:

      • Adaptive cruise control
      • Forward collision warning
      • Blind spot monitoring
      • Rear cross traffic alert
      • Automatic high-beam headlights
      • Rain-sensing windshield wipers
      • Rear parking sensors

      Challenger Dimensions and Weight

      The Challenger is 16.5 feet long, and its curb weight ranges from 3,841 to 4,481 pounds.

      Where Is the 2022 Dodge Challenger Built?

      Dodge builds the 2022 Challenger in Canada.

      When Did the Dodge Challenger First Come Out?

      The Dodge Challenger was introduced for the 1970 model year, at the height of the pony car craze, to compete with the Ford Mustang that started it all in 1964. The inaugural Challenger models featured straight-six-cylinder and V8 engines, including the 425-horsepower, 7.0-liter Hemi. The Challenger's first generation ceased production in 1974. The second generation began with the 1978 Dodge Colt Challenger, which was a smaller and much less powerful sporty coupe. Production of this generation was outsourced to Mitsubishi, and instead of six- and eight-cylinder engines, this crop of Challengers featured a lineup of four-cylinder mills. The second-generation Challenger ended in 1983.

      The third, and current, generation launched for the 2008 model year as a modern muscle car with retro first-generation-inspired styling. Its bulky, squared-off design and four headlights along with insanely powered engines pay homage to the original Challengers.

      Which Dodge Challenger Model Is Right for Me?

      The 2022 Dodge Challenger comes in seven trims: SXT, GT, R/T, R/T Scat Pack, SRT Hellcat, SRT Hellcat Redeye, and SRT Super Stock. Each trim generally features a different engine, and that should be the main factor driving your purchasing decision.

      SXT and GT models come with a V6, and they're the only trims available with all-wheel drive. R/T and R/T Scat Pack models have powerful Hemi engines, and they come with more standard features than lower trims. For most shoppers, these are the best combination of performance and value.

      Dodge Challenger SXT

      The 2022 Dodge Challenger SXT comes standard with a 303-horsepower V6 engine, an eight-speed automatic transmission, and rear-wheel drive; all-wheel drive is optional. Standard features include cloth upholstery, a six-way power-adjustable driver's seat, a leather-wrapped steering wheel and shift knob, a rearview camera, dual-zone automatic climate control, proximity keyless entry, and a 7-inch touch-screen infotainment system with Bluetooth, Android Auto, Apple CarPlay, two USB ports, and a six-speaker stereo.

      There are numerous optional features available for the base model, including Nappa leather upholstery, heated and ventilated front seats, an 8.4-inch touch screen, navigation, satellite radio, and a six- or nine-speaker Alpine premium stereo. Also available are a sunroof, a universal garage door opener, remote start, driver's seat and steering wheel memory settings, a power tilt-and-telescoping steering wheel, and a heated steering wheel.

      Most active safety features are only available as options, no matter the trim. That list includes adaptive cruise control, forward collision warning, blind spot monitoring, rear cross traffic alert, automatic high-beam headlights, rain-sensing windshield wipers, and rear parking sensors.

      Dodge Challenger GT

      The Dodge Challenger GT has the same standard V6 and RWD powertrain of the base model, and it's the only other trim available with AWD. The GT's added features include upgraded cloth upholstery, a universal garage door opener, rear parking sensors, a performance steering wheel with paddle shifters, projector fog lights, and performance brakes, steering, and suspension.

      Additional optional features include Brembo performance brakes, a high-performance suspension, Nappa leather and Alcantara suede upholstery, a flat-bottom steering wheel, and an 18-speaker Harman Kardon surround-sound stereo.

      Dodge Challenger R/T

      The Dodge Challenger R/T features a 5.7-liter Hemi V8 engine, a performance exhaust, and an upgraded rear axle. The Hemi is rated at 375 horsepower with a standard six-speed manual transmission, and its 372 horsepower with an optional eight-speed automatic.

      Dodge Challenger R/T Scat Pack

      The Dodge Challenger Scat Pack comes with a 485-horsepower 6.4-liter Hemi V8, Brembo performance brakes, launch control, a high-performance suspension, and SRT drive modes. Its additional comfort features include an 8.4-inch touch screen, satellite radio, a six-speaker Alpine sound system, heated front seats, and a heated steering wheel.

      Newly optional features for this trim include six-piston drilled and slotted Brembo front brakes, an adaptive damping suspension, drag race radial tires, and a suede-wrapped steering wheel.

      Dodge Challenger SRT Hellcat

      The Dodge Challenger SRT Hellcat features a supercharged 6.2-liter V8 engine that makes 717 horsepower. This high-performance trim also includes six-piston Brembo front brakes, a heavy-duty differential, an open-air intake, and a competition three-mode adjustable Bilstein suspension. Full Laguna leather upholstery is optional.

      The Dodge Challenger SRT Hellcat Redeye has a 797-horsepower version of the supercharged V8, while the Dodge Challenger SRT Hellcat Super Stock makes 807 horsepower and features street-legal drag race tires.

      Check out our U.S. News Best Price Program for great savings at your local Dodge dealer. You can also find excellent manufacturer incentives on our Dodge deals page .

      See 2022 Dodge Challenger specs and trims

      The Final Call

      The 2022 Dodge Challenger prioritizes powerful engines above all else, but a standout amount of interior and trunk space also helps set it apart from other sports cars . It's a good buy if youre looking for supercarlike power or a retro-looking muscle car, but if you want a fresh-feeling cabin or engaging handling, check out some other class rivals.

      Don't just take our word for it. Check out comments from some of the reviews that drive our rankings and analysis.

      • "The 2022 Dodge Challenger is a national treasure. It represents that most American of automobiles the muscle car. And it sure packs a lot of muscle." -- Kelley Blue Book
      • "TheDodge Challengeris an antidote to mainstream vehicles. Its retro styling has the right look. Its engines range from a strong V6 with 303 horsepower to a drag strip-incinerating 807-hp V8. Yet with a spacious rear seat and loads of trunk space, its even a coupe for families." -- Autotrader (2021)
      • "The Challenger concedes points to rivals when it comes to interior refinement and sporty driving dynamics. But drivers who value comfort and utility will likely prefer the Dodge." -- Edmunds (2020)
